11:55.882 --> 11:58.635
We call those nod.
Shakes are these.

11:58.635 --> 12:00.303
<i>- What I'm gonna do</i>
<i>for my through tang is just weld</i>

12:00.303 --> 12:02.222
one of the structural bolts on.

12:02.222 --> 12:05.141
It'll save a lot of time,
because it's already threaded.

12:05.141 --> 12:07.143
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:07.143 --> 12:09.229
I know I have
a lot to grind off.

12:09.229 --> 12:12.232
And I just have to go
for the quench.

12:12.232 --> 12:13.900
- It looks like
Chad just quenched.

12:13.900 --> 12:15.401
I was not expecting that.

12:15.401 --> 12:16.986
- No.
- I think Chad feels like

12:16.986 --> 12:18.905
he's so far behind
at this point

12:18.905 --> 12:21.991
that he just needs to get
as much done as he possibly can.

12:21.991 --> 12:24.160
- [bleep].
The piece ain't hard.

12:24.160 --> 12:25.912
I've had
a really rough day.

12:25.912 --> 12:27.705
<i>I gotta do a second quench,</i>

12:27.705 --> 12:30.541
and I just need this
to work out for me.

12:30.541 --> 12:34.295
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:34.295 --> 12:36.965
- John just quenched.
Huge fireball over here.

12:36.965 --> 12:39.008
<i>- I feel like</i>
<i>it's a good quench,</i>

12:39.008 --> 12:42.262
but I don't really have time
to allow the thing

12:42.262 --> 12:44.138
<i>to cool off sufficiently</i>

12:44.138 --> 12:46.266
to actually do a file check,

12:46.266 --> 12:48.685
<i>because I've still got to get</i>
<i>a threaded tang on here.</i>

12:48.685 --> 12:50.520
<i>And with 20 minutes,</i>

12:50.520 --> 12:52.730
<i>I don't have enough time</i>
<i>to grind or forge</i>

12:52.730 --> 12:55.775
the end of that tang
down to the proper size

12:55.775 --> 12:57.902
to actually cut threads on it.

12:57.902 --> 13:00.113
<i>And I'm nervous</i>
<i>because it's getting close</i>

13:00.113 --> 13:03.866
<i>to the size parameter.</i>

13:03.866 --> 13:08.204
- Chad's in the quench again.
- All right.

13:08.204 --> 13:10.915
Aaron just quenched.

13:10.915 --> 13:14.460
- Aaron, please don't catch
your face on fire!

13:14.460 --> 13:17.714
<i>- All right, Wil, I understand.</i>

13:17.714 --> 13:21.384
I don't have model hands,
I got a model face.

13:21.384 --> 13:23.094
- Josh has not quenched yet.

13:23.094 --> 13:24.762
- So he's the only one
who hasn't quenched.

13:24.762 --> 13:26.431
- That's right.
<i>- Time's running out,</i>

13:26.431 --> 13:28.891
<i>and I still need</i>
<i>to do the heat treat,</i>

13:28.891 --> 13:30.810
and I know
I have to thread the tang.

13:30.810 --> 13:32.937
- Wow, come on, Josh.

13:32.937 --> 13:34.647
You've got
to quench that blade.

13:34.647 --> 13:36.190
<i>- I'm really worried</i>
<i>about a warp,</i>

13:36.190 --> 13:38.109
<i>but I just have to quench</i>

13:38.109 --> 13:41.946
and hope that it's good enough.

13:41.946 --> 13:45.825
- Ten, nine, eight, seven,

13:45.825 --> 13:48.911
six, five, four,

13:48.911 --> 13:52.040
three, two, one!

13:52.040 --> 13:55.043
Bladesmiths, shut down
your machines, drop your tools!

13:55.043 --> 13:56.753
This forging round is over!

13:56.753 --> 13:59.088
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:59.088 --> 14:01.549
<i>- I'm proud that</i>
<i>I made this blade.</i>

14:01.549 --> 14:03.926
I don't think it's beautiful.

14:03.926 --> 14:06.179
<i>I don't know if it's gonna be</i>
<i>better than everybody else.</i>

14:06.179 --> 14:09.807
But I am just proud
of what I did.

14:09.807 --> 14:12.852
- Bladesmiths, that was
an interesting first round.

14:12.852 --> 14:14.437
Now it's time for the judges
to take a look

14:14.437 --> 14:16.314
at the work that you've done.

14:16.314 --> 14:18.024
Aaron, you're up first.

14:18.024 --> 14:19.484
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:19.484 --> 14:21.527
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:21.527 --> 14:23.613
<i>- Right now,</i>
<i>it's got a good profile,</i>

14:23.613 --> 14:25.698
but it's like a knife blank,

14:25.698 --> 14:28.659
because your spine is as thick
as your edge over here.

14:28.659 --> 14:32.038
We can see a big crack
right here on the edge

14:32.038 --> 14:33.498
that travels from one side

14:33.498 --> 14:35.666
all the way to the other.

14:35.666 --> 14:37.668
If you do move forward, aside
from that issue right there,

14:37.668 --> 14:39.337
I'd like you to think
about the handle.

14:39.337 --> 14:41.631
It's very big.
- Josh,

14:41.631 --> 14:43.174
the only one of our smiths

14:43.174 --> 14:44.675
that didn't start over
from scratch,

14:44.675 --> 14:48.513
please present
your work to the judges.

14:48.513 --> 14:51.349
- Of all of our smiths, you were
the one that took the longest

14:51.349 --> 14:53.768
in your setup, and it paid off.

14:53.768 --> 14:56.896
The fact that I can see
that there's that 1095 edge

14:56.896 --> 15:00.233
all the way down this blade
is just fantastic.

15:00.233 --> 15:02.110
- There's quite a warp
in this blade.

15:02.110 --> 15:05.530
I mean--you could have,
like, little kids on either side

15:05.530 --> 15:08.282
playing a little teeter-totter
game on this thing.

15:08.282 --> 15:10.076
- Chad, you're up.

15:10.076 --> 15:13.371
Please present your blade
to the judges.

15:13.371 --> 15:16.124
- Your second canister, I mean,
that's beautiful steel.

15:16.124 --> 15:18.835
I mean, there's a couple little
cosmetic cracks here and there,

15:18.835 --> 15:21.796
but generally speaking,
that's beautifully welded.

15:21.796 --> 15:24.966
A really long handle,
but that can be addressed.

15:24.966 --> 15:27.093
Got a nice amount of mass to it,
almost too much.

15:27.093 --> 15:30.179
Like, I'd like to see quite
a bit of this stripped away.

15:30.179 --> 15:31.806
- John, you're up.

15:31.806 --> 15:33.015
Please present your blade
to the judges.

15:33.015 --> 15:34.976
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:34.976 --> 15:37.728
- That's a really neat bush
knife shape.

15:37.728 --> 15:39.313
But more than anything,

15:39.313 --> 15:41.440
what I see up here
along the spine

15:41.440 --> 15:43.609
<i>are a lot of cosmetic issues.</i>

15:43.609 --> 15:45.736
This is the big concern for me,

15:45.736 --> 15:47.321
<i>that one that</i>
<i>you can see traveling</i>

15:47.321 --> 15:48.948
<i>all the way across there.</i>

15:48.948 --> 15:50.908
Any impact,
this lower third

15:50.908 --> 15:53.953
of the blade
is just gonna overweight this.

15:53.953 --> 15:55.538
- All right, bladesmiths,

15:55.538 --> 15:57.123
the judges have
a decision to make.

15:57.123 --> 15:58.583
While they do that,
I'm gonna ask you

15:58.583 --> 15:59.834
to leave your blades
on this table

15:59.834 --> 16:00.918
and step off The Forge floor.

16:00.918 --> 16:08.885
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:08.885 --> 16:10.511
- That was rough.
- That was terrible.

16:10.511 --> 16:12.305
[laughter]
- All right, gentlemen,

16:12.305 --> 16:14.015
our bladesmiths have finished

16:14.015 --> 16:16.726
their nuts and bolts
canister Damascus blades.

16:16.726 --> 16:20.021
They should be
between 12 and 15 inches long.

16:20.021 --> 16:22.940
Let's get into the details.
We're gonna start with Chad.

16:22.940 --> 16:24.108
- [sighs]

16:24.108 --> 16:25.985
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:25.985 --> 16:28.779
- It's pretty darn straight.
It's heavy.

16:28.779 --> 16:30.239
There's a lot of meat
there that he can take off,

16:30.239 --> 16:32.992
but it's a clean piece
of steel.

16:32.992 --> 16:37.872
- All right, let's go ahead
and move on to Josh's blade.

16:37.872 --> 16:40.583
- Unfortunately he waited
until the end to quench,

16:40.583 --> 16:43.211
and he didn't have time
to deal with that warp.

16:43.211 --> 16:46.547
Not too happy
about those threads.

16:46.547 --> 16:48.007
They're awfully small.

16:48.007 --> 16:49.717
- Let's move on
to Aaron's blade.

16:49.717 --> 16:52.011
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:52.011 --> 16:55.014
<i>- You can see the crack</i>
<i>right here go across.</i>

16:55.014 --> 16:56.849
<i>That's telling me that</i>
<i>it's already cracked in half.</i>

16:56.849 --> 16:58.601
While we hit--
and that's the spot

16:58.601 --> 16:59.936
that we're going for--
it's gonna break off.

16:59.936 --> 17:01.854
He would have to re-profile this

17:01.854 --> 17:04.232
and redesign the whole blade
to make it passable

17:04.232 --> 17:06.067
if he makes it
to the second round.

17:06.067 --> 17:07.944
- Okay, let's move on
to our last bladesmith,

17:07.944 --> 17:10.571
and that's John.

17:10.571 --> 17:13.366
- Most of this, to me,
looks like it's cosmetic.

17:13.366 --> 17:15.368
If he were to put
a peat spine on this,

17:15.368 --> 17:17.078
just bevel these two edges,

17:17.078 --> 17:19.372
he'd remove
most of these cracks.

17:19.372 --> 17:24.168
But it looks big to me.

17:24.168 --> 17:26.087
- They're looking at it
pretty good.

17:26.087 --> 17:27.505
- I know I'm really close
to that

17:27.505 --> 17:33.886
overall length on there.

17:33.886 --> 17:36.097
- Bladesmiths, before
the first round begins,

17:36.097 --> 17:38.558
we tell you to pay attention
to the details.

17:38.558 --> 17:42.478
Failure to meet parameters
is a self-elimination.

17:42.478 --> 17:45.481
John, your blade
did not meet the parameters

17:45.481 --> 17:47.525
for this challenge.

17:47.525 --> 17:49.902
- John, we have those parameters
for a reason,

17:49.902 --> 17:52.780
and your blade exceeded
our maximum length.

17:52.780 --> 17:54.490
That's why
we're letting you go.

17:54.490 --> 17:57.076
- John, please
surrender your blade.

17:57.076 --> 17:59.161
<i>- I'm heartbroken.</i>

17:59.161 --> 18:03.374
To fail in this way, it's just
a really terrible mistake.

18:03.374 --> 18:08.004
But I gotta keep on doing
what I do, because if I give up

18:08.004 --> 18:09.589
after one mistake,

18:09.589 --> 18:11.424
bladesmithing isn't for me.

18:14.135 --> 18:16.178
- Congratulations, bladesmiths.

18:16.178 --> 18:18.264
You've made it to the second
round of this competition.

18:18.264 --> 18:20.224
Now that your blade's
been tempered,

18:20.224 --> 18:22.059
it's time to turn them
into fully-functional weapons

18:22.059 --> 18:24.186
by attaching handles to them.

18:24.186 --> 18:28.566
But, your blades must maintain
that threaded-through tang,

18:28.566 --> 18:32.737
and you need to add
a metal screw-on pommel.

18:32.737 --> 18:35.239
You will have three hours
in this round.

18:35.239 --> 18:38.409
Good luck, bladesmiths.
Your three hours starts now.

18:38.409 --> 18:40.453
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:40.453 --> 18:42.663
A lot of work to be done here

18:42.663 --> 18:44.707
in the second round
of competition.

18:44.707 --> 18:46.292
Let's start with Aaron,

18:46.292 --> 18:48.586
our contestant that dodged
the judges' bullet

18:48.586 --> 18:51.088
because another smith
missed the parameters.

18:51.088 --> 18:54.216
- He's got a lot of work, then.
He's got a crack that's fatal.

18:54.216 --> 18:57.053
- If it wasn't for John
not meeting the parameters,

18:57.053 --> 18:58.721
<i>I was leaving.</i>

18:58.721 --> 19:01.766
I have to make sure
my blade is solid.

19:01.766 --> 19:04.769
- Dave, you're the fix-it man.
How do you fix it?

19:04.769 --> 19:07.480
- I say, weld up that big crack,
flip it over,

19:07.480 --> 19:09.482
and sharpen what used
to be the spine.

19:09.482 --> 19:11.442
<i>- I'm putting the crack</i>
<i>on the spine.</i>

19:11.442 --> 19:14.236
I'm sharpening
the other side, baby.

19:14.236 --> 19:16.238
<i>- The judges told me I had</i>
<i>a lot of weight on my blade.</i>

19:16.238 --> 19:18.741
So I'm just hoping that
with some grinding,

19:18.741 --> 19:20.409
I'm able to fix this problem.

19:20.409 --> 19:22.244
- At this point, for Chad,
it seems like

19:22.244 --> 19:25.206
it's all refinement
of his overall geometry.

19:25.206 --> 19:27.041
<i>- I don't want to grind</i>
<i>too much,</i>

19:27.041 --> 19:28.876
<i>'cause I don't want</i>
<i>too thin of an edge.</i>

19:28.876 --> 19:32.588
So hopefully I can get a nice,
even medium on this.

19:32.588 --> 19:34.882
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:34.882 --> 19:37.927
- Josh over here has one of
the more severely warped blades

19:37.927 --> 19:40.054
we've ever had coming
into a round two.

19:40.054 --> 19:41.806
- It's quite a warp.

19:41.806 --> 19:43.265
- Now, we have acetylene
torches out there.

19:43.265 --> 19:45.142
Would he be better
served to use those?

19:45.142 --> 19:46.644
<i>- Oh, yeah.</i>
<i>- Absolutely, yeah.</i>

19:46.644 --> 19:48.104
You can localize the heat
a lot better

19:48.104 --> 19:50.147
with a really, really hot flame.

19:50.147 --> 19:52.692
This is just a waste of time.

19:52.692 --> 19:55.778
- I'm frustrated.
This is taking too long.

19:55.778 --> 19:57.697
- I'm really nervous at Josh.

19:57.697 --> 20:00.324
I've seen people get so
involved with straightening

20:00.324 --> 20:03.202
that they forget
time management.

20:03.202 --> 20:05.246
<i>- I'm in a little bit</i>
<i>of panic mode.</i>

20:05.246 --> 20:07.498
I'm not getting any results.

20:07.498 --> 20:09.250
I don't know about this.

20:09.250 --> 20:11.419
<i>I definitely</i>
<i>may not get this done.</i>

20:11.419 --> 20:12.013
Oh, [bleep].

20:14.797 --> 20:17.425
<i>- I've spent one hour</i>
<i>straightening this blade,</i>

20:17.425 --> 20:20.428
and I'm not getting
any results.

20:20.428 --> 20:22.179
<i>I don't have</i>
<i>a handle on the blade.</i>

20:22.179 --> 20:24.014
<i>I don't have a pommel.</i>

20:24.014 --> 20:26.726
I don't have the threads
on the tang corrected.

20:26.726 --> 20:28.686
Can't spend any more
time on it.

20:28.686 --> 20:32.982
<i>I made the effort.</i>
<i>I just have to move on.</i>

20:32.982 --> 20:35.776
<i>- I got my profile right,</i>
<i>all the weight's off.</i>

20:35.776 --> 20:37.278
I think it's about time
to put the handle on.

20:37.278 --> 20:39.488
That's some hard [bleep].

20:39.488 --> 20:41.157
Micarta's one of
the best materials

20:41.157 --> 20:43.701
that you can use
for an abusive test.

20:43.701 --> 20:45.494
That's all I need.

20:45.494 --> 20:46.704
And then I want to go
with a brass pommel

20:46.704 --> 20:48.497
because it's gonna look nice,

20:48.497 --> 20:49.874
<i>and it's gonna thread</i>
<i>really easily.</i>

20:49.874 --> 20:52.334
- Chad's really just
moving along, man.

20:52.334 --> 20:54.003
- Yeah. I think he's
doing really well.

20:54.003 --> 20:55.212
- Like a glove.

20:55.212 --> 20:56.714
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:56.714 --> 20:58.048
<i>- I already picked out</i>

20:58.048 --> 20:59.967
<i>the micarta for the handle.</i>

20:59.967 --> 21:02.470
But I have to focus
on my pommel,

21:02.470 --> 21:06.348
because I've never threaded it,
or even used one.

21:06.348 --> 21:08.851
Damn it.
- So Aaron's got

21:08.851 --> 21:11.312
the ratcheting die
and he's struggling.

21:11.312 --> 21:14.356
- [bleep] this tap and die.
Can't see a [bleep] damn

21:14.356 --> 21:15.858
number on it.

21:15.858 --> 21:17.193
I didn't realize
I had bad eyesight

21:17.193 --> 21:19.111
until I got here.

21:19.111 --> 21:20.529
Oh, [bleep].

21:20.529 --> 21:22.281
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:22.281 --> 21:24.033
[bleep], yeah.

21:24.033 --> 21:27.036
I finally get the pommel
threaded properly,

21:27.036 --> 21:28.078
<i>and it all goes</i>
<i>together great.</i>

21:28.078 --> 21:29.455
Yes.

21:29.455 --> 21:30.915
- Two hours has elapsed.

21:30.915 --> 21:32.708
You have one hour remaining

21:32.708 --> 21:34.919
to finish your blades.

21:34.919 --> 21:36.921
<i>- One hour left, I don't have</i>
<i>a handle on the blade,</i>

21:36.921 --> 21:40.174
<i>and I don't have the threads</i>
<i>on the tang corrected.</i>

21:40.174 --> 21:42.343
I have a lot to do in an hour.

21:42.343 --> 21:47.097
- I'm noticing that Josh's once
calm and very fluid movements

21:47.097 --> 21:50.100
are now becoming
erratic and panicked.

21:50.100 --> 21:52.019
<i>- I thread the tang</i>
<i>pretty quickly.</i>

21:52.019 --> 21:54.396
<i>Now I have to thread the pommel</i>

21:54.396 --> 21:59.568
and get myself set up
to complete a handle.

21:59.568 --> 22:00.778
<i>- At this point</i>
<i>in the challenge,</i>

22:00.778 --> 22:02.321
<i>compared to the first round,</i>

22:02.321 --> 22:03.572
I'm doing a lot better.

22:03.572 --> 22:05.032
<i>I've completed my handle.</i>

22:05.032 --> 22:07.201
I'm feeling pretty good
with it,

22:07.201 --> 22:09.995
<i>but I want to make sure my blade</i>
<i>is presentable for the judges,</i>

22:09.995 --> 22:12.039
<i>so I decided to etch.</i>

22:12.039 --> 22:14.083
The reason why I wanted
to put in the acid etching

22:14.083 --> 22:15.835
<i>is I want to show</i>
<i>the judges the bolts</i>

22:15.835 --> 22:18.337
<i>and everything</i>
<i>that was put into this.</i>

22:18.337 --> 22:21.757
I do believe that I have
a great chance of winning.

22:21.757 --> 22:23.384
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:23.384 --> 22:25.135
<i>- I love doing handles.</i>

22:25.135 --> 22:28.305
To me, that is where
a lot of the beauty is.

22:28.305 --> 22:30.307
<i>I got everything epoxied.</i>

22:30.307 --> 22:32.393
<i>I'm gonna cut out</i>
<i>a profile for this handle.</i>

22:32.393 --> 22:34.687
<i>Everything's gonna be cool.</i>
<i>We're nearing the finish.</i>

22:34.687 --> 22:37.273
Oh, come on.

22:37.273 --> 22:40.609
Five-minute epoxy
is bull[bleep].

22:40.609 --> 22:42.987
<i>This epoxy has not set up yet.</i>

22:42.987 --> 22:47.867
Time is running out, and shaping
the handle is gonna be horrible.

22:47.867 --> 22:49.994
I don't have time to do it.

22:49.994 --> 22:52.663
- Aaron's handle's
looking really skinny.

22:52.663 --> 22:55.499
- It has an interesting shape
as well.

22:55.499 --> 22:57.418
Josh has his blade all taped up,

22:57.418 --> 22:59.837
and he's really trying
to get this handle

22:59.837 --> 23:01.338
into a comfortable shape,

23:01.338 --> 23:03.757
and doesn't have a lot of time.

23:03.757 --> 23:06.135
<i>- I've got 15 minutes</i>
<i>to shape a handle,</i>

23:06.135 --> 23:07.720
and I'm ready to go to battle,

23:07.720 --> 23:10.472
'cause I know it's
gonna be a big mess.

23:10.472 --> 23:12.349
I'm struggling with not
turning in a blade

23:12.349 --> 23:14.476
that I'm 100% proud of,

23:14.476 --> 23:18.063
'cause I want to showcase
my abilities and my skill,

23:18.063 --> 23:20.816
and I'm not sure if this
blade's gonna do that for me.

23:20.816 --> 23:22.985
[bleep].

23:22.985 --> 23:25.863
- Don't swear.
Your mother's watching this.

23:25.863 --> 23:30.951
- Five, four, three, two, one!

23:30.951 --> 23:33.621
Bladesmiths, shut down
your machines! Drop your tools!

23:33.621 --> 23:36.874
This second round
of competition has ended.

23:36.874 --> 23:38.459
- In the history of
"Forged in Fire,"

23:38.459 --> 23:41.128
maybe the worst-looking
handle ever.

23:41.128 --> 23:44.673
It's functional.
It's not pretty.

23:44.673 --> 23:46.800
- Gentlemen, to test
the strength of your edge

23:46.800 --> 23:49.011
as well as the overall
construction of your blades,

23:49.011 --> 23:51.722
I'm gonna be batonning them
three times into these bolts.

23:51.722 --> 23:53.933
Remember, this is all about what
the bolts do to your blades,

23:53.933 --> 23:55.976
and not what your blades
do to the bolts.

23:55.976 --> 23:58.646
Aaron, you're up. You ready?

23:58.646 --> 24:01.857
- Yes.

24:01.857 --> 24:04.360
<i>I'm afraid Ben's</i>
<i>gonna break my blade.</i>

24:04.360 --> 24:07.446
<i>The way he hits,</i>
<i>I'm scared that this blade</i>

24:07.446 --> 24:10.574
<i>is gonna snap in half.</i>

24:10.574 --> 24:17.581
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:24.254 --> 24:27.633
- Well, Aaron,
there's blade damage here.

24:27.633 --> 24:30.386
There's a significant roll
right at this spot right here,

24:30.386 --> 24:33.013
and I can get my fingernail
underneath it.

24:33.013 --> 24:35.766
The handle is a little
interesting to me.

24:35.766 --> 24:37.893
I can see you left
these two points here

24:37.893 --> 24:39.728
because of the pins you put in.

24:39.728 --> 24:41.438
But that creates
a finger well up here

24:41.438 --> 24:44.608
that's pushing my finger
towards the blade.

24:44.608 --> 24:46.819
Josh, you're up.
- I'm so ready.

24:46.819 --> 24:53.784
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:08.048 --> 25:10.217
- Well, Josh,
there's a cool little feature

25:10.217 --> 25:12.344
that started happening
back here.

25:12.344 --> 25:14.304
- I see that.

25:14.304 --> 25:16.306
- It's part of the screw
that was in this pocket here,

25:16.306 --> 25:19.309
so it just wasn't
fully welded together.

25:19.309 --> 25:21.812
There is edge deflection
here from the last hit.

25:21.812 --> 25:24.440
I can get my fingernail
underneath it.

25:24.440 --> 25:26.734
Still has a pretty
significant warp.

25:26.734 --> 25:30.070
But in general, the whole
blade held up. Well done.

25:30.070 --> 25:31.947
- Thank you.
- Chad, you're up. You ready?

25:31.947 --> 25:34.992
- Yep.

25:34.992 --> 25:36.577
<i>With batonning,</i>
<i>that's a lot of force</i>

25:36.577 --> 25:38.328
<i>to put on the back</i>
<i>of a knife.</i>

25:38.328 --> 25:40.539
<i>But I test my knives</i>
<i>like this at home.</i>

25:40.539 --> 25:43.500
So I believe that
it'll be okay.

25:43.500 --> 25:50.507
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:57.056 --> 25:58.766
- Well, Chad,
first thing's first.

25:58.766 --> 26:01.602
There are two relatively
big deflections here.

26:01.602 --> 26:03.353
They're kind of just mushes.

26:03.353 --> 26:06.148
They're not really edge
rolls or chips.

26:06.148 --> 26:08.692
But aside from those,
the blade is still straight

26:08.692 --> 26:10.819
and in one piece.
Well done.

26:10.819 --> 26:13.739
- Thank you.

26:13.739 --> 26:15.699
- Bladesmiths,
to test the sharpness,

26:15.699 --> 26:17.201
I will take your weapon,

26:17.201 --> 26:19.495
and I will slice
and dice these hams.

26:19.495 --> 26:20.996
Aaron, you're up first.
Are you ready?

26:20.996 --> 26:21.955
- Yes, sir.

26:21.955 --> 26:28.837
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:38.847 --> 26:41.809
- All right, Aaron,
your handle over here.

26:41.809 --> 26:44.311
It's comfortable
on the back side, but you know,

26:44.311 --> 26:46.480
the point that you
have over here,

26:46.480 --> 26:50.400
it pushes my finger close to the
ricasso where the edge starts.

26:50.400 --> 26:53.862
But overall, it sliced
and diced evenly.

26:53.862 --> 26:56.490
There's no curing that ham.
It will cut.

26:56.490 --> 26:58.659
- Thank you, sir.
- How about you, Josh?

26:58.659 --> 27:00.244
- I'm ready like
a Christmas ham.

27:00.244 --> 27:07.084
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:20.681 --> 27:23.100
- All right, Josh,
let's talk about your blade.

27:23.100 --> 27:27.145
Your edge, though it took some
damage, no issues whatsoever.

27:27.145 --> 27:30.232
It's sharp, and it's got
a good cutting feel to it.

27:30.232 --> 27:32.609
Overall, it will cut.

27:32.609 --> 27:34.778
- Thank you.
- Chad, it's your turn.

27:34.778 --> 27:36.071
You ready?
- Yes, sir.

27:36.071 --> 27:42.995
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:54.172 --> 27:56.800
- [exhales]

27:56.800 --> 27:58.093
- All right, Chad.

27:58.093 --> 28:01.513
I am impressed with your blade.

28:01.513 --> 28:04.016
Because even though,
on the strength test,

28:04.016 --> 28:05.183
it took in some damage,

28:05.183 --> 28:07.686
it sliced evenly and without

28:07.686 --> 28:09.438
any issues whatsoever.

28:09.438 --> 28:12.274
Overall, your blade will cut.

28:12.274 --> 28:15.193
- Thank you.
- Good job.

28:15.193 --> 28:17.863
- Bladesmiths, the judges'
deliberation is complete,

28:17.863 --> 28:20.699
and a final
decision has been made.

28:20.699 --> 28:22.326
The bladesmith
leaving the forge is...

28:22.326 --> 28:23.552
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:25.954 --> 28:30.751
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:30.751 --> 28:33.962
Aaron, your blade
did not make the cut.

28:33.962 --> 28:36.798
- Aaron, all the blades
took some kind of damage

28:36.798 --> 28:38.800
on the strength test.

28:38.800 --> 28:41.386
All the blades cut beautifully
on the sharpness test.

28:41.386 --> 28:43.639
So it came down to your handle.

28:43.639 --> 28:47.017
<i>Your handle just puts our index</i>
<i>finger so close to that edge</i>

28:47.017 --> 28:49.227
<i>that if you were to</i>
<i>use it vigorously,</i>

28:49.227 --> 28:50.896
it's eventually gonna cut us.

28:50.896 --> 28:53.440
For that reason,
we're letting you go.

28:53.440 --> 28:55.651
- Aaron, you may
surrender your blade.

28:55.651 --> 28:57.569
<i>- When it comes to handles</i>
<i>on knives,</i>

28:57.569 --> 28:59.780
they have to fit
the hand properly.

28:59.780 --> 29:02.115
<i>And mine was just not up to par.</i>

29:02.115 --> 29:05.619
But this was the greatest
time of my life.

29:05.619 --> 29:10.540
And I am so proud to be here.

29:10.540 --> 29:12.501
- Josh, Chad, congratulations.

29:12.501 --> 29:16.505
All you need to do now is defeat
the man standing next to you

29:16.505 --> 29:18.548
in our final round
of competition,

29:18.548 --> 29:21.301
in which we send you back to
your home forges for five days

29:21.301 --> 29:24.179
to re-create an iconic weapon
from history.

29:26.848 --> 29:29.518
A pair of bagh nakh.

29:29.518 --> 29:31.353
- Wow.

29:31.353 --> 29:33.397
<i>- Meaning "tigers claw,"</i>
<i>the bagh nakh</i>

29:33.397 --> 29:35.983
<i>was a ruthless</i>
<i>weapon originating from India.</i>

29:35.983 --> 29:37.526
<i>While concealed in the hand,</i>

29:37.526 --> 29:38.819
<i>it could serve up</i>
<i>surprise attacks</i>

29:38.819 --> 29:40.737
<i>resulting in deep gashes</i>

29:40.737 --> 29:42.781
<i>that pierce through</i>
<i>both skin and muscle.</i>

29:42.781 --> 29:45.325
<i>This variation was called</i>
<i>a bichwa bagh nakh,</i>

29:45.325 --> 29:47.411
<i>and included a lethal blade</i>

29:47.411 --> 29:49.371
<i>that was made to resemble</i>
<i>the sting of a scorpion.</i>

29:49.371 --> 29:51.248
<i>This design made it</i>
<i>a triple threat,</i>

29:51.248 --> 29:53.417
<i>where it could either</i>
<i>thrust, slash, or claw</i>

29:53.417 --> 29:55.419
<i>its way into an opponent.</i>

29:55.419 --> 29:57.379
<i>One of the most well-known</i>
<i>uses of the weapon</i>

29:57.379 --> 29:59.464
<i>is recounted in the history</i>
<i>of the Maratha Empire,</i>

29:59.464 --> 30:02.509
<i>when Emperor Shivaji</i>
<i>secretly wore a bagh nakh</i>

30:02.509 --> 30:07.723
<i>and fatally disemboweled</i>
<i>his enemy.</i>

30:07.723 --> 30:10.434
They must be a matched
set of bagh nakh.

30:10.434 --> 30:14.479
Your blades must include
two integral finger rings,

30:14.479 --> 30:19.026
four sharpened claws,
and a thumb rise on each blade.

30:19.026 --> 30:21.737
- What is that? Doc nakh?

30:21.737 --> 30:24.781
Do-- [bleep] I don't even know
how to say it.

30:24.781 --> 30:27.284
<i>[bleep].</i>
<i>It's tiger claw, there you go.</i>

30:27.284 --> 30:28.994
- You will have five days
at your home forges

30:28.994 --> 30:30.787
to complete this challenge.

30:30.787 --> 30:32.497
At the end of those five days,
you will return

30:32.497 --> 30:33.874
and present your bagh nakh

30:33.874 --> 30:35.834
to our panel of expert judges.

30:35.834 --> 30:37.753
Only after they've
thoroughly tested them

30:37.753 --> 30:40.172
will they declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion

30:40.172 --> 30:42.382
and hand you that check
for ten grand.

30:42.382 --> 30:46.344
Good luck, bladesmiths.
We'll see you in five days.

30:46.344 --> 30:47.429
both: Good luck.

30:47.429 --> 30:50.265
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:50.265 --> 30:52.684
<i>- We're building</i>
<i>the bagh nakh bichwa.</i>

30:52.684 --> 30:54.728
Two knives, actually.

30:54.728 --> 30:56.897
<i>Day one is to drift</i>
<i>the loop for the fingers.</i>

30:56.897 --> 30:58.648
<i>I need to keep the placement</i>

30:58.648 --> 31:00.901
<i>of the fingers the same</i>
<i>on both blades,</i>

31:00.901 --> 31:04.112
<i>because any discomfort in</i>
<i>holding it could be a problem.</i>

31:04.112 --> 31:07.282
I want to keep the blade in line
with the fingers, straight line,

31:07.282 --> 31:10.118
right through the fingers,
right to the tip.

31:10.118 --> 31:12.370
<i>I've got all four holes</i>
<i>drifted.</i>

31:12.370 --> 31:14.372
<i>The rest of the time, I plan</i>
<i>to start working on the claws,</i>

31:14.372 --> 31:16.249
<i>which is gonna be a challenge.</i>

31:16.249 --> 31:18.168
<i>I've got to work</i>
<i>on each one individually.</i>

31:18.168 --> 31:20.170
<i>I have to keep them</i>
<i>the same the entire time.</i>

31:20.170 --> 31:23.757
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:23.757 --> 31:25.759
<i>- I'm at my home forge.</i>
<i>I'm excited.</i>

31:25.759 --> 31:27.928
Let's get this started.

31:27.928 --> 31:30.514
<i>I'm using Damascus, 'cause</i>
<i>if it comes down to aesthetics,</i>

31:30.514 --> 31:33.600
that might give me
an edge to my competitor.

31:33.600 --> 31:36.311
<i>I want a nice, bold pattern, and</i>
<i>hope that at the end of the day</i>

31:36.311 --> 31:38.146
<i>I have the billets done.</i>

31:38.146 --> 31:39.981
That turned out beautiful.

31:42.359 --> 31:45.362
- The plan for today,
I have to attach the claws.

31:45.362 --> 31:47.697
<i>I want these claws to be</i>
<i>lined up with one another--</i>

31:47.697 --> 31:49.908
equal spacing.

31:49.908 --> 31:51.576
<i>If I weld one of these claws</i>
<i>and it's out of position,</i>

31:51.576 --> 31:53.578
there's no way
I'm getting it off easily.

31:53.578 --> 31:57.499
So I have to be careful.
They're actually pretty good.

31:57.499 --> 32:00.544
Now that I've got the claws in,
the next step is heat treat.

32:00.544 --> 32:02.087
<i>A lot of things can go wrong.</i>

32:02.087 --> 32:04.089
I can overshoot the temperature

32:04.089 --> 32:05.632
and create problems
in the steel,

32:05.632 --> 32:07.509
especially at the tip
of the blade.

32:07.509 --> 32:11.012
<i>Overheating would make</i>
<i>it easier to break.</i>

32:11.012 --> 32:17.686
<i>If it cracks or warps,</i>
<i>I start over again.</i>

32:17.686 --> 32:19.437
Oh, [bleep].

32:19.437 --> 32:21.606
It looks like it took a warp.

32:21.606 --> 32:23.191
I hope I'm wrong.

32:23.191 --> 32:25.488
Because I don't have time
to start over.

32:28.947 --> 32:32.075
Maybe not.

32:32.075 --> 32:34.077
It's pretty straight.

32:34.077 --> 32:36.037
I don't know if I'm
seeing things or what.

32:36.037 --> 32:38.039
<i>Seemed to me</i>
<i>like it was warped,</i>

32:38.039 --> 32:40.542
and then I just didn't do
anything, and it got straight.

32:40.542 --> 32:43.170
<i>When I quenched the second</i>
<i>blade, just beautiful.</i>

32:43.170 --> 32:45.088
I can't believe that I got both
these blades

32:45.088 --> 32:46.506
through heat treat.

32:46.506 --> 32:49.259
They look pretty good.

32:49.259 --> 32:52.888
<i>- Today I'll make the claws and</i>
<i>get them attached to my blade.</i>

32:52.888 --> 32:55.724
I'm liking it.
Claws are even.

32:55.724 --> 32:58.143
It's time to get ready
for heat treat.

32:58.143 --> 33:01.438
<i>There's five blades that</i>
<i>I have to treat on one blade.</i>

33:01.438 --> 33:03.231
<i>So it's very difficult.</i>

33:03.231 --> 33:05.066
[laughs]

33:05.066 --> 33:06.902
That is a very straight blade.

33:06.902 --> 33:09.696
Time for the second one.

33:12.949 --> 33:16.328
I'm liking it.
It looks really nice.

33:16.328 --> 33:18.413
<i>- It's awesome to have</i>
<i>the heat treat behind me.</i>

33:18.413 --> 33:20.081
<i>I'm pretty much done.</i>

33:20.081 --> 33:22.083
The rest of it is
just fine detail work.

33:22.083 --> 33:24.419
<i>The thing I'm most proud of</i>
<i>are the design elements</i>

33:24.419 --> 33:26.087
<i>that I put into the blade.</i>

33:26.087 --> 33:28.381
<i>I love the poured</i>
<i>black handle.</i>

33:28.381 --> 33:31.092
<i>and the stark contrast between</i>
<i>the handle and the blade.</i>

33:31.092 --> 33:33.720
<i>The tiger eye stones</i>
<i>really bring</i>

33:33.720 --> 33:36.181
<i>the whole thing</i>
<i>together as a tiger claw.</i>

33:36.181 --> 33:38.183
<i>There's a little scorpion</i>
<i>stinger at the back, too.</i>

33:41.102 --> 33:43.688
<i>- Today I want to put on the</i>
<i>leather wrap for the handles.</i>

33:43.688 --> 33:47.108
<i>Kind of two purposes for that--</i>
<i>to give it a little extra grip,</i>

33:47.108 --> 33:50.278
and to conceal the welds
that I put on there.

33:50.278 --> 33:52.739
I'll test it
and see if I like it.

33:52.739 --> 33:55.700
<i>I think it'll be sufficient</i>
<i>for stabbing.</i>

33:55.700 --> 33:59.746
It can take a lot of abuse,
and also has a sharp edge.

33:59.746 --> 34:05.877
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:05.877 --> 34:08.129
It's sharp.

34:08.129 --> 34:10.048
I feel really confident
about these blades.

34:10.048 --> 34:11.800
<i>I can't wait to see them</i>
<i>being tested.</i>

34:11.800 --> 34:15.387
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:15.387 --> 34:17.597
- Bladesmiths, welcome back
to The Forge.

34:17.597 --> 34:19.516
You've had five days
at your home forges to work

34:19.516 --> 34:21.559
on your finale weapons.

34:21.559 --> 34:23.812
Josh, how did it go?
- Well, you guys asked

34:23.812 --> 34:25.146
for the tiger claw,
I think I brought you

34:25.146 --> 34:26.940
the whole tiger.

34:26.940 --> 34:29.484
<i>I forged out the blade</i>
<i>in spring steel.</i>

34:29.484 --> 34:32.570
<i>The claws are through the handle</i>
<i>and welded from the back.</i>

34:32.570 --> 34:36.408
- Great.
Chad, tell us about your blades.

34:36.408 --> 34:39.077
<i>- I did a Damascus, 153 layers.</i>

34:39.077 --> 34:41.079
<i>I hand-forged most of it.</i>

34:41.079 --> 34:45.208
The claws, they're made
out of 1095. They'll hold up.

34:45.208 --> 34:47.836
- All right, gentlemen.
Your weapons look fantastic.

34:47.836 --> 34:50.297
It's time to see how they
hold up in our weapons test.

34:50.297 --> 34:53.675
And we will lead it all off
with a kill test. Doug.

34:53.675 --> 34:56.303
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:56.303 --> 34:58.471
- Bladesmiths, to see
what kind of lethal damage

34:58.471 --> 35:00.515
your weapon will do,
we'll take your bagh nakh

35:00.515 --> 35:03.101
and deliver multiple slashes
and thrusts

35:03.101 --> 35:06.187
and claw
at this pig carcass.

35:06.187 --> 35:07.772
Josh, you're up first.
You ready for this?

35:07.772 --> 35:09.816
- So ready.

35:09.816 --> 35:11.568
<i>My heart is beating</i>
<i>out of my chest,</i>

35:11.568 --> 35:13.737
and I'm just trying
to calm myself.

35:13.737 --> 35:17.741
But I'm pretty confident
that it's gonna perform well.

35:17.741 --> 35:20.827
- To be my tiger claw today,
please welcome back

35:20.827 --> 35:22.954
my brother RJ Marcaida.

35:24.497 --> 35:31.379
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:53.193 --> 35:56.696
- All right, Josh.
First up, it's comfortable.

35:56.696 --> 35:59.866
My three fingers in the middle
allow me to grasp on

35:59.866 --> 36:01.451
to the claws easily

36:01.451 --> 36:03.620
and not feel
that it's gonna impede

36:03.620 --> 36:05.205
my movement with the hand.

36:05.205 --> 36:07.248
The clawing is very deep.

36:07.248 --> 36:10.085
Your slashes cut deep
into this pig carcass.

36:10.085 --> 36:14.422
Overall, your bagh nakh
will kill. Good job.

36:14.422 --> 36:16.466
- Thank you.
- All right, Chad. Your turn.

36:16.466 --> 36:18.718
You ready?
- Yes, sir.

36:18.718 --> 36:20.428
<i>The only thing that I'm really</i>
<i>hoping to hear right now</i>

36:20.428 --> 36:22.764
is just Doug
will say, "It'll kill."

36:22.764 --> 36:26.476
'Cause that's a pretty
big accomplishment.

36:26.476 --> 36:33.483
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:48.998 --> 36:50.583
- All right, Chad.
First off,

36:50.583 --> 36:52.669
the handle,
it's on the thinner side.

36:52.669 --> 36:54.838
There's a little bit
of movement there.

36:54.838 --> 36:57.674
But the positions
where you have the claw,

36:57.674 --> 36:59.592
it's secure, it's safe.

36:59.592 --> 37:01.177
They're razor sharp.

37:01.177 --> 37:03.304
On the lacerations there
and the slicing,

37:03.304 --> 37:05.056
it cuts deeply.

37:05.056 --> 37:07.559
Overall, your weapon will kill.

37:07.559 --> 37:09.936
- Thank you.
- Well, RJ, I can see

37:09.936 --> 37:12.188
your fighting skills have
not changed since we were kids.

37:12.188 --> 37:13.732
You still scratch like a girl.

37:13.732 --> 37:16.109
Cat claws.
[hissing]

37:16.109 --> 37:17.902
[laughter]

37:17.902 --> 37:20.488
Thank you very much.
I hope you had a lot of fun.

37:20.488 --> 37:25.744
Next up is the strength test.
Ben.

37:25.744 --> 37:27.287
- Bladesmiths, to test
the strength

37:27.287 --> 37:29.164
and durability
of your bagh nakh,

37:29.164 --> 37:32.041
I'm gonna be clawing
and stabbing away at these logs.

37:32.041 --> 37:34.586
Remember, this test is all about
what happens to your blades,

37:34.586 --> 37:36.421
not what happens to the log.

37:36.421 --> 37:37.505
Josh, you're up first.
You ready?

37:37.505 --> 37:39.758
- I'm ready.

37:39.758 --> 37:42.135
<i>I'm nervous</i>
<i>about the strength test.</i>

37:42.135 --> 37:43.636
I'm worried about the tip,
because the tip

37:43.636 --> 37:45.764
is the thinnest part
of the blade.

37:45.764 --> 37:47.932
<i>There's a chance of a fracture.</i>

37:49.809 --> 37:56.775
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:09.245 --> 38:12.207
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

38:12.207 --> 38:13.291
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:13.291 --> 38:14.876
- Well, Josh, your claws

38:14.876 --> 38:16.127
held up very well.

38:16.127 --> 38:17.670
There's no mark on them

38:17.670 --> 38:19.756
